{
  "Igneous rocks form from:": "",
  "Compacted sediments": "",
  "Chemical precipitation from water": "",
  "Heat and pressure applied to existing rocks": "",
  "Cooled and solidified magma or lava": "",
  "Igneous rocks form when molten rock (magma below the surface or lava at the surface) cools and solidifies. The word 'igneous' comes from the Latin word for fire.": "",
  "Intrusive igneous rocks have large crystals because they:": "",
  "Were formed from dissolved minerals in water": "",
  "Cooled slowly underground, giving crystals time to grow": "",
  "Cooled quickly at the surface": "",
  "Were subjected to extreme pressure": "",
  "Intrusive (plutonic) igneous rocks cool slowly deep within the Earth, allowing mineral crystals plenty of time to grow large. Granite is a classic example with its visible crystals of quartz, feldspar, and mica.": "",
  "Sedimentary rocks form through the processes of:": "",
  "Extreme heat and pressure": "",
  "Weathering, erosion, deposition, compaction, and cementation": "",
  "Volcanic eruption only": "",
  "Melting and crystallization": "",
  "Sedimentary rocks form when rock fragments, organic material, or dissolved minerals are transported, deposited in layers, and then compacted and cemented together over time. This multi-step process is part of the rock cycle.": "",
  "Metamorphic rocks are formed when existing rocks are changed by:": "",
  "Melting completely into magma": "",
  "Erosion and deposition": "",
  "Rapid cooling at the surface": "",
  "Heat and/or pressure without fully melting": "",
  "Metamorphic rocks form when pre-existing rocks are subjected to elevated temperature and/or pressure that changes their mineral composition and texture without completely melting them. If the rock fully melts, it becomes magma.": "",
  "Granite is an example of a(n):": "",
  "Intrusive igneous rock": "",
  "Extrusive igneous rock": "",
  "Foliated metamorphic rock": "",
  "Sedimentary rock": "",
  "Granite is an intrusive igneous rock that forms from the slow cooling of magma deep within the Earth. Its coarse-grained texture with visible crystals of quartz, feldspar, and mica is a direct result of its slow cooling history.": "",
  "Which of the following is a clastic sedimentary rock?": "",
  "Obsidian": "",
  "Sandstone": "",
  "Limestone": "",
  "Marble": "",
  "Sandstone is a clastic sedimentary rock made of sand-sized fragments of pre-existing rocks that have been compacted and cemented together. Clastic rocks are classified by their grain size.": "",
  "Foliated metamorphic rocks are characterized by:": "",
  "Aligned minerals creating a banded or layered appearance": "",
  "Gas bubbles from volcanic activity": "",
  "Random crystal arrangement": "",
  "Visible fossils": "",
  "Foliation occurs when minerals in metamorphic rocks align perpendicular to the direction of pressure, creating visible bands or layers. Slate, schist, and gneiss are common examples of foliated metamorphic rocks.": "",
  "Extrusive igneous rocks typically have:": "",
  "Large, visible crystals": "",
  "Fossils embedded in the rock": "",
  "Visible layers and bands": "",
  "Fine-grained or glassy texture due to rapid cooling": "",
  "Extrusive (volcanic) igneous rocks cool rapidly at or near Earth's surface, leaving little time for crystals to grow. This produces fine-grained textures (like basalt) or even glassy textures (like obsidian).": "",
  "Limestone that is subjected to intense heat and pressure becomes:": "",
  "Slate": "",
  "Quartzite": "",
  "Gneiss": "",
  "When limestone (a sedimentary rock composed of calcite) is subjected to heat and pressure, it recrystallizes into marble, a non-foliated metamorphic rock with a distinctly different interlocking crystal texture.": "",
  "The rock cycle is driven primarily by:": "",
  "Earth's internal heat and surface energy from the Sun": "",
  "Gravity alone, particularly regarding": "",
  "Only water erosion within the typical": "",
  "Wind alone, particularly regarding": "",
  "The rock cycle is powered by two major energy sources: Earth's internal heat (driving metamorphism, melting, and plate tectonics) and energy from the Sun (driving weathering, erosion, and the water cycle at the surface).": "",
  "What is the rock cycle?": "",
  "The process by which only sedimentary rocks form from igneous rocks": "",
  "The continuous process by which rocks are created, transformed from one type to another, and recycled through geological processes": "",
  "The annual pattern of rock erosion caused by seasonal weather changes": "",
  "A one-way process where rocks form and never change again": "",
  "The rock cycle is the continuous series of geological processes through which the three rock types (igneous, sedimentary, and metamorphic) are created, destroyed, and transformed into each other. It has no fixed beginning or end point.": "",
  "What is weathering?": "",
  "The breakdown of rocks at or near Earth's surface by physical, chemical, or biological processes": "",
  "The transport of rock fragments by wind, water, or ice": "",
  "The deposition of sediments in layers at the bottom of a lake": "",
  "The melting of rock deep inside the Earth": "",
  "Weathering is the breakdown of rocks into smaller fragments at or near Earth's surface. Physical weathering breaks rock mechanically, chemical weathering alters mineral composition, and biological weathering involves organisms like plant roots.": "",
  "What is a clastic sedimentary rock?": "",
  "A rock formed from the remains of ancient organisms": "",
  "A rock formed from broken fragments of pre-existing rocks that are compacted and cemented together": "",
  "A rock formed when minerals precipitate from evaporating water": "",
  "A rock formed from the cooling of magma underground": "",
  "Clastic sedimentary rocks are composed of fragments (clasts) of pre-existing rocks that have been weathered, transported, deposited, and then compacted and cemented. They are classified by grain size: shale (clay), siltstone, sandstone (sand), and conglomerate (gravel).": "",
  "What is foliation in metamorphic rocks?": "",
  "The process of cementing sediment grains together": "",
  "The presence of fossils within the rock layers": "",
  "The formation of gas bubbles as magma cools": "",
  "The alignment of mineral grains into parallel layers or bands caused by directed pressure": "",
  "Foliation is a texture in metamorphic rocks where mineral grains align perpendicular to the direction of compressive stress, creating a layered or banded appearance. The degree of foliation increases with metamorphic grade, from slate to phyllite to schist to gneiss.": "",
  "What does 'cementation' mean in sedimentary rock formation?": "",
  "The process by which dissolved minerals precipitate in the spaces between sediment grains, binding them together": "",
  "The transport of sediments by flowing water": "",
  "The process of melting rocks at extreme temperatures": "",
  "The physical squeezing of sediments under weight": "",
  "Cementation is the process where minerals dissolved in groundwater (commonly silica, calcite, or iron oxides) precipitate in the pore spaces between sediment particles, essentially gluing them together to form solid sedimentary rock.": "",
  "What is an extrusive igneous rock?": "",
  "A rock that forms when lava cools rapidly at or near Earth's surface, producing fine-grained or glassy texture": "",
  "A rock that forms from compressed plant material over millions of years": "",
  "A rock that forms when existing rocks are altered by extreme pressure": "",
  "A rock that forms when magma cools slowly deep underground": "",
  "Extrusive (volcanic) igneous rocks form when lava erupts at the surface and cools quickly, preventing large crystals from forming. This rapid cooling produces fine-grained textures like basalt or glassy textures like obsidian.": "",
  "What does 'metamorphism' mean?": "",
  "The deposition of sediments in a river delta": "",
  "The change in form, mineral composition, and texture of existing rock caused by heat, pressure, or chemical fluids without complete melting": "",
  "The complete melting and re-cooling of rock": "",
  "The breaking apart of rocks by weathering and erosion": "",
  "Metamorphism (from Greek for 'change of form') is the transformation of existing rock into a new form through heat, pressure, or chemically active fluids. The key distinction is that metamorphism occurs in the solid state without complete melting.": "",
  "What is an organic sedimentary rock?": "",
  "A rock that forms from the accumulation of biological remains like shells, plant material, or skeletal fragments": "",
  "A rock that is used as fertilizer in organic farming": "",
  "A rock formed from volcanic material mixed with soil": "",
  "A rock that contains only carbon-based minerals": "",
  "Organic sedimentary rocks form from the accumulated remains of organisms. Coal forms from compacted plant material, while some limestones and chalk form from the accumulated shells and skeletons of marine organisms.": "",
  "What is compaction in sedimentary rock formation?": "",
  "The transport of sediment by wind or water to a new location": "",
  "The pressing together of sediment layers under the weight of overlying material, reducing pore space": "",
  "The crystallization of minerals from cooling magma": "",
  "The chemical breakdown of rock minerals by acidic water": "",
  "Compaction occurs when layers of sediment are squeezed together under the weight of overlying deposits. This pressure reduces the space between grains and expels water, which is the first step in turning loose sediment into solid rock.": "",
  "What is a chemical sedimentary rock?": "",
  "A rock formed from cooled volcanic lava flows": "",
  "A rock altered by contact with hot magma": "",
  "A rock that forms when dissolved minerals precipitate out of water solution": "",
  "A rock formed from pieces of other rocks cemented together": "",
  "Chemical sedimentary rocks form when minerals dissolved in water precipitate out of solution, usually through evaporation or chemical reactions. Examples include rock salt (halite), gypsum deposits, and some types of limestone.": "",
  "A hiker picks up a rock from a mountain trail and notices it has visible bands of light and dark minerals. A geologist identifies it as gneiss. Based on the rock cycle, which explanation of its formation is most accurate?": "",
  "It formed when an asteroid impact melted the surrounding rock": "",
  "It formed when layers of sand were deposited and cemented together": "",
  "It formed when a pre-existing rock was subjected to intense heat and pressure deep underground, causing minerals to separate into alternating bands": "",
  "It formed from lava cooling on the surface of a volcano": "",
  "Gneiss is a high-grade foliated metamorphic rock that forms under intense heat and pressure deep within the Earth. The characteristic alternating light and dark bands result from mineral segregation during metamorphism.": "",
  "Construction workers quarrying stone notice that the rock at their site contains visible fossils of ancient sea creatures, yet the quarry is located hundreds of kilometers from the nearest ocean. What does this evidence reveal?": "",
  "Volcanic eruptions transported marine material to the interior of the continent": "",
  "The area was once covered by ocean where marine sediments accumulated and were later lithified into sedimentary rock, then uplifted": "",
  "The fossils were carried there by ancient humans": "",
  "Sea creatures evolved on land before migrating to the ocean": "",
  "Marine fossils found far from today's oceans indicate that the area was once covered by a shallow sea. Sedimentary rocks with marine fossils formed on the seafloor and were later uplifted by tectonic forces.": "",
  "A geology student examines two rock samples with the same mineral composition. Sample A has large, visible crystals while Sample B has extremely fine grains. Both are igneous rocks. What caused the difference in texture?": "",
  "Sample A cooled slowly underground (intrusive), while Sample B cooled rapidly at the surface (extrusive)": "",
  "Sample B was exposed to more pressure than Sample A": "",
  "Sample A is older than Sample B": "",
  "Sample A contains more minerals than Sample B": "",
  "Cooling rate determines crystal size in igneous rocks. Slow cooling underground gives minerals time to form large, visible crystals (intrusive rocks like granite), while rapid cooling at the surface produces tiny crystals (extrusive rocks like rhyolite).": "",
  "After a devastating wildfire, a park ranger notices that some sandstone outcrops near the fire zone appear to have changed color and texture compared to unburned areas. What rock cycle process might this localized heating represent?": "",
  "Contact metamorphism on a minor scale, where heat from the fire altered the minerals near the surface": "",
  "Erosion, because the heat wore away the rock surface": "",
  "Igneous rock formation, because the fire melted the sandstone into magma": "",
  "Sedimentation, because the ash settled on the rock surface": "",
  "Extreme heat from a wildfire can cause minor thermal alteration of surface rocks, which is a small-scale example of contact metamorphism. While far less intense than geological metamorphism, the principle is the same: heat changes the mineral structure.": "",
  "A scientist studying climate history drills a core from a sedimentary formation and finds coral fossils at the bottom, sandstone in the middle, and coal at the top. What sequence of environments does this suggest?": "",
  "All three layers formed simultaneously in different parts of the same lake": "",
  "The area was always a tropical forest that experienced flooding": "",
  "The area transitioned from a shallow marine environment (coral) to a sandy setting (sandstone) to a swampy lowland (coal)": "",
  "The rocks were rearranged by an earthquake and do not represent a time sequence": "",
  "Sedimentary layers record environmental changes over time. Coral fossils indicate a warm, shallow marine environment. Sandstone suggests a transition to a sandy coastal setting. Coal at the top indicates a swampy, vegetation-rich lowland.": "",
  "A road crew cuts through a hillside and exposes dark basalt on one side and lighter, altered rock with new minerals near the contact zone. What process created the altered rock?": "",
  "Chemical precipitation from groundwater flowing through cracks": "",
  "Sedimentation of new minerals on top of the basalt": "",
  "Weathering from exposure to rain and wind": "",
  "Contact metamorphism, where heat from the intruding magma altered the surrounding rock": "",
  "Contact metamorphism occurs when hot magma intrudes into surrounding rock, heating it and causing mineral changes near the contact zone. The altered rock (contact aureole) shows new minerals and textures formed in response to the heat.": "",
  "A farmer in the Midwest frequently turns up rounded pebbles and cobbles of various rock types mixed in with clay. A geologist explains these are glacial till. What does this tell us about the rock cycle processes that shaped this landscape?": "",
  "The rocks are metamorphic fragments created by deep crustal pressure": "",
  "A volcanic eruption scattered rock fragments across the landscape": "",
  "Ancient glaciers eroded, transported, and deposited rock fragments from diverse sources, and these sediments may someday become sedimentary rock": "",
  "The pebbles formed in place from chemical precipitation": "",
  "Glacial till is unsorted sediment deposited directly by glaciers, containing fragments of many different rock types. This represents the erosion and deposition stages of the rock cycle, and if buried and compacted, this till could eventually become sedimentary rock.": "",
  "A coastal city is considering using locally quarried limestone as a building material. An engineer warns that limestone may be vulnerable to acid rain. Why is this concern valid?": "",
  "Limestone is composed of calcium carbonate, which dissolves when it reacts with the carbonic and sulfuric acids in acid rain": "",
  "Limestone is too soft to withstand any weather conditions": "",
  "Limestone contains iron that rusts when exposed to acid": "",
  "Acid rain only affects igneous rocks, not sedimentary rocks": "",
  "Limestone is composed primarily of calcite (calcium carbonate), which readily reacts with acids. Acid rain dissolves calcite, causing the rock to weather and deteriorate over time. This chemical weathering is part of the rock cycle.": "",
  "A geologist discovers slate in a region known to have once been covered by a shallow sea where mudstone accumulated. She determines the mudstone was later buried and compressed during a mountain-building event. What rock cycle pathway does this represent?": "",
  "Igneous to metamorphic to sedimentary": "",
  "Volcanic eruption followed by chemical weathering": "",
  "Metamorphic to igneous to sedimentary": "",
  "Sedimentary formation (mudstone from marine sediments) followed by metamorphism (converting mudstone to slate)": "",
  "This illustrates a classic rock cycle pathway: marine sediments were deposited and lithified into mudstone (sedimentary rock), which was then subjected to heat and pressure during a mountain-building event, transforming it into slate (metamorphism).": "",
  "Researchers find a volcanic island where basalt lava is being weathered by tropical rain, and the sediments wash into a lagoon where they are slowly accumulating. In millions of years, these sediments could become sedimentary rock, then be subducted and metamorphosed. What principle does this illustrate?": "",
  "Rocks can only change form once before being permanently fixed": "",
  "Only igneous rocks can participate in the rock cycle": "",
  "The rock cycle only operates on continental landmasses": "",
  "The rock cycle is a continuous loop where material is constantly recycled, and any rock type can eventually become any other type": "",
  "This scenario demonstrates the fundamental principle of the rock cycle: material is continuously recycled. Igneous basalt weathers into sediments, which may become sedimentary rock, which may later be metamorphosed. The cycle has no beginning or end.": ""
}